Our sources of information for the life of the poet . Tibullus are of the'most scanty description. Of the little that we know by far the greater part is derived from the incidental notices of himself and his doings which are scattered here and there throughout his writ- ings. The short Biography transcribed above adds but little to what he himself tells us, except the fact that he died young. ln addition, we have an Epigram by a contemporary, Marsus Domitius, referred to in the same Biography3 two of the poems of Horace-Odes 1. 33 and Epistles 1. 4-are addressed to a poet Albius, whom the learned have unanimously identified with the poet Tibullus3 while there are frequent references to him in the works of Ovid.
